i1.name: Saburo's Sushi House
i1.commentary: where my earliest memories of sushi begin, earmarking many celebrations and occasions.

i2.name: Musashi's
i2.commentary: Cozy. Chirashi bowl after every final.

i3.name: Sushi K Kamizato
i3.commentary: A shop lined with metal and rock music memorabilia. The most unique omakase experience I've ever had.

i5.name: 後壁湖邱家生魚片
i5.commentary: On the southern tip of Taiwan, tabletop full of sashimi and traditional Taiwanese dishes, I witnessed a king crab attempt to escape its enclosure here.

i1.name: Beef
i1.commentary: I wish this show came out  when I was younger. Younger me needed to see fully-realized Asian-American characters onscreen. I resonated with them, in all their glory and brokenness, and their mannerisms and behaviors, uniquely and distinctively Asian and American.

i2.name: Better Call Saul
i2.commentary: Breaking Bad would’ve made the list too if I hadn’t seen it so long ago. I’m fascinated by Saul’s journey, from his flirting with the morally dubious, to his Cinnabon-laden reckoning.

i3.name: Mad Men
i3.commentary: I used to joke that growing up was watching Mad Men and thinking you’re Don Draper but eventually realizing you’re Pete Campbell.

i4.name: Master of None
i4.commentary: I’ve watched Master of None a couple of times now. I’d go as far as saying that it kindled my romance with NYC. It made me want to leave Portland and the suburbs I grew up in.

i1.name: Lower Mcleay to Pittock Mansion
i1.commentary: It was the proximity. Or maybe the view. Just comfortable, just challenging enough.

i2.name: Mailbox Peak Trail Loop
i2.commentary: My redemption for skipping leg day.

i3.name: Bridal Veil Falls & Lunch Rock via Lake Serene
i3.commentary: I bought micro-spikes just for this.

i4.name: Angel's Landing
i4.commentary: Where I learned I was okay with heights.

i5.name: Rim, Navajo Loop & Peakaboo
i5.commentary: Bring water and a sense of wonder.

i1.name: 1990 Toyota Previa
i1.commentary: This egg-shaped minivan had a mid-engine platform making it more spiritually similar to supercars than family haulers.

i2.name: 2001 Pontiac Aztek
i2.commentary: It was aesthetically hard to love but I find its outdoorsy vibes charming.

i3.name: 2005 Honda CR-V
i3.commentary: The pinnacle of vehicle engineering. There's a picnic table in the trunk. Also I drive one.

i4.name: 2003 Saab 9-3
i4.commentary: The layout of the car made you feel like you were in a fighter jet.

i5.name: 2003 Honda Element
i5.commentary: Mechanically the same as my CR-V but optimized for dog ownership.

content.name: seattle coffee shops
content.commentary: study and journal to smoky dark roasts
